The paper proposes a benchmarking framework for graph neural networks (GNNs) and evaluates the effectiveness of different GNN architectures on various datasets from different domains such as mathematical modeling, computer vision, chemistry, and combinatorial problems. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), social and information networks (cs.SI), and computational linguistics (cs.CL).
